South African Corn Advances, Tracking Gains by U.S. Benchmark

-- B y   M k h u l u l i   M a n c o t y w a
-- 
2011-02-14T10:51:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-14/south-african-corn-advances-tracking-gains-by-u-s-benchmark.html
Corn advanced in  South Africa , the
continent’s largest producer of the grain, as prices rose in the
U.S., which competes for African export markets.  White corn for July delivery added 30 rand, or 1.7 percent,
to end trade at 1,746 rand ($240) a metric ton on the  South
African Futures Exchange  in Johannesburg. Meal made from the
grain is the country’s staple food.  Corn futures for May delivery rose 7.75 cents, or 1.1
percent, to $7.1725 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade on
Feb. 11 and gained 0.3 percent to $7.1925 in electronic trading
today.  Yellow corn for July delivery gained 23.20 rand, or 1.3
percent, to 1,787.20 rand a ton. The grain is used mainly as  animal feed  in  South Africa .  Wheat for March delivery increased 34 rand, or 1 percent,
to 3,425 rand a ton.  The gains or losses for the most active contracts of the
following crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
and the crops are sold in tons:  To contact the reporter on this story:
